You need two pieces: a **navigation guard** in `AppShell` and a **custom back button** on the page.

### 1. Guard navigation in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

Use `OnNavigating` with `GetDeferral()` for the async dialog:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `GetDeferral()` is required for async checks — without it, navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- `args.Cancel()` stops the navigation if the user taps "Stay".
- Check `ShellNavigationSource.Pop` so the guard only fires on back navigation.

### 2. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage"
             Title="Edit Product">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 3. ViewModel command

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
private async Task Cancel()
{
    // This triggers OnNavigating, which shows the guard dialog
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` **replaces** the default back action, so your command must call `GoToAsync("..")` explicitly. That pop triggers `OnNavigating`, where the guard dialog runs. This gives you a single confirmation path regardless of whether the user taps your "Cancel" button or uses a swipe-back gesture.
